                 "attributionTitle":  "å½’å±ž",
                 "faqSection":  "å¸¸è§é—®é¢˜",
                 "faqTitle":  "å¸¸è§é—®é¢˜",
                 "technicalSection":  "æŠ€æœ¯",
                 "techTitle":  "æŠ€æœ¯æ¦‚è¿°",
                 "devTitle":  "æœ¬åœ°å¼€å‘",
                 "repoTitle":  "ä»“åº“ç»“æž„",
                 "contributingSection":  "è´¡çŒ®",
                 "contributingTitle":  "è´¡çŒ®",
                 "techCopy":  "The project is a static site hosted on Render. The frontend is vanilla HTML, CSS, and JavaScript with no framework dependencies. Internationalization (i18n) is handled client-side with JSON locale files. The dashboard is fully client-side rendered from static CSV data.",
                 "whyCopy":  "Crypto ecosystems rely on public infrastructure, but contribution is scattered across many repositories. This project makes that work easier to inspect by consolidating merged PRs into a single view, organized by contributor, project, organization, and ecosystem.",
                 "faqMergedQuestion":  "Why only merged PRs?",
                 "trackedTitle":  "Tracked transparently",
                 "whatCopy":  "Proof of Contribution is an open-source dashboard that tracks merged pull requests across crypto ecosystems. It turns public GitHub data into a searchable, filterable contribution map — showing who builds, where they contribute, and which projects concentrate open-source activity.",
                 "faqMergedAnswer":  "Merged PRs represent accepted contributions — work that was reviewed and integrated. This provides a clearer signal of meaningful contribution than raw activity metrics such as issues or comments.",
                 "dataIntro":  "How we collect, organize, and keep fresh the information you see on the dashboard.",
                 "faqFreshnessQuestion":  "How often is the data updated?",
                 "measureCopy":  "The dashboard focuses on merged pull requests by contributor, organization, project, and date. Metrics include: total PRs per contributor, number of contributors per ecosystem, project-level activity, and contribution concentration across ecosystems.",
                 "trackedCopy":  "All contributors to this project are tracked transparently through the dashboard itself.",
                 "metricsIntro":  "What we count, what we don\u0027t, and how contributions are attributed.",
                 "contributingIntro":  "This project is open source. Contributions are welcome.",
                 "freshnessCopy":  "The dataset is refreshed periodically. Each refresh captures the latest merged PRs from tracked organizations. New contributors, projects, and PRs appear after the next successful refresh cycle.",
                 "faqEcosystemQuestion":  "Can I add a new ecosystem?",
                 "howCopy":  "The project periodically fetches merged pull request data from GitHub\u0027s public API for tracked organizations. The data is processed, aggregated, and served as static CSV files. The dashboard reads these files and renders the contribution layer in the browser.",
                 "collectionCopy":  "Data is collected through GitHub\u0027s public API using the Search endpoint for merged pull requests. The collection process is fully open-source and reproducible. Collection scripts reside in the repository for anyone to inspect or run independently.",
                 "contributingCopy":  "To add a new ecosystem, submit a pull request updating the collection configuration. To report issues, suggest features, or ask questions, open an issue on \u003ca href=\"https://github.com/alerodriargui/proof-of-contribution\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer\"\u003eGitHub\u003c/a\u003e.",
                 "attributionCopy":  "Contributions are attributed to GitHub usernames as they appear in merged PR author fields. Bot accounts are identified and can be filtered out. GHOST — GitHub\u0027s placeholder for deleted or unavailable users — is also identified in the dataset.",
                 "technicalIntro":  "Architecture, local setup, and repository layout for developers.",
                 "repoCopy":  "The main application lives in \u003ccode\u003eapp/\u003c/code\u003e. Data collection scripts are in \u003ccode\u003escripts/\u003c/code\u003e. CSV data files are at the repository root. Locale files for i18n are in \u003ccode\u003eapp/locales/\u003c/code\u003e. The contributor detail page is at \u003ccode\u003econtributors/\u003c/code\u003e.",
                 "faqBotsQuestion":  "How are bot accounts handled?",
                 "limitationsCopy":  "This project measures merged PRs only. It does not track issues, comments, code reviews, or other forms of contribution. Additionally, only public repositories in tracked organizations are included. Data is as fresh as the last refresh cycle.",
                 "faqEcosystemAnswer":  "Yes. The collection scripts are open-source. See the Contributing section below or the repository README for instructions.",
                 "faqFreshnessAnswer":  "The dataset is refreshed periodically. Check the repository for the latest refresh schedule.",
                 "ecosystemsCopy":  "The project currently indexes merged PRs from multiple crypto ecosystems. Each ecosystem is defined as a set of organizations on GitHub. The full list of tracked ecosystems and organizations is available in the project repository\u0027s configuration.",
                 "faqBotsAnswer":  "Accounts identified as bots are flagged in the dashboard filters. You can choose to hide or show them using the filter controls. GHOST (deleted accounts) is shown separately.",
